Transactional data :

f

In March 2017, the average daily sales of small & big machines are 7058 & 14666 respectively.

#Adding a new column in the txns datarame called month
txns$month = month(as.Date(txns$timestamp))

#Calculating number of unique days
unique_days_in_march = length(unique((txns %>% filter(month==3))$date))

#Calculating the avg daily sales for small & big machines in March
txns %>% 
    filter(month==3) %>%
    group_by(machine) %>%
    summarise(total_sales_in_march = n()) %>%
    left_join(machines, by='machine') %>%
    select(machine, total_sales_in_march, small_machine) %>%
    aggregate(total_sales_in_march ~ small_machine, FUN = sum) %>%
    mutate(avg_daily_sales_in_march =  round(total_sales_in_march/unique_days_in_march)) %>%
    select(small_machine, avg_daily_sales_in_march)
  small_machine avg_daily_sales_in_march
1             0                    14666
2             1                     7058

Potential reasons for this difference :

  • The small machines by definition have lesser storage capacity and once they are out of stock, it usually takes a day or two to replenish them.

  • It is possible that big machines have more variety of products and hence higher sales.

  • It is also possible that the small machines hold products from a category that has lower average prices.

Question-2

a

Yes, there seems to be a general trend in the number of sales of both snacks & drinks. This trend is same for both snacks & drinks. The general trend for both snacks & drinks is as follows :

In a given month, there seem to be 4 peak (same peak days for both snacks & drinks) days where the sales of both snacks & drinks shoot up. It so happens that these peak days are Mondays. On Monday, people get back to work and are usually less motived to work. They probably require some snacks or drinks to keep them going and hence this peak in sales every Monday.

b

Yes, there also seems to be a shorter time period trend. This is not same for snacks & drinks. As we go from January (winter) to April (Spring) the temperature increases and hence the sales of drinks shoot up. For snacks though, the trend is generally stable with a slight dip when the months are March & April.

Question-3

a

The income_average column in machines data does contain outliers. This can be seen by plotting the histogram for this particular column.

hist(machines$income_average, 
     main='Histogram of income_average before outlier removal')

These outliers need to be removed, as the abnormal high value of the income_average for these instances will cause bias in the linear model that will be created later in this exercise. In this case, it is a good idea to remove outliers that are above & below 1.5 times the inter-quartile range. The following code block depicts the necessary steps

#Calculating the interquartile range
quantiles = quantile(machines$income_average, na.rm=TRUE)
iqr = quantiles[4]-quantiles[2]


machines <- machines %>% 
          filter(is.na(income_average)|income_average <= quantiles[4]+(1.5*iqr)) %>%
          filter(is.na(income_average)|income_average >= quantiles[2]-(1.5*iqr))

After removing the outliers, the machines dataframe contains 2311 observations (184 outliers were removed) Now that the outliers have been removed, lets plot the histogram again for the same data.

hist(machines$income_average, 
     main='Histogram of income_average after outlier removal')

b

There are 4 ways of treating missing values of the income_average column. They are mentioned below :

  1. Dropping the rows which have income_average as NA.

  2. Replace NAs by a particular value using the replace_na() function.

  3. Fill NAs with the previous or next value using the fill() function.

  4. Fill NAs using aggregate values like mean or median.

We go ahead with final option i.e.Â we replace the NAs by mean of the income_average column. This is because we know that there are 182 NAs in income_average(~8% of the data). We do not want to lose information about other features for these 182 instances as we believe that 8% is a sizable portion of data. The reason behind filling the NAs with mean instead of other constant value or the previous or next value is that we have arrived from the previous question that the distribution of the income_average column is almost normal and hence imputing the NAs with mean makes sense. Please find the code below :

machines$income_average[is.na(machines$income_average)] <- mean(machines$income_average, 
                                                                na.rm=TRUE)

Checking the distribution of income_average column.

summary(machines$income_average)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  31570   48637   53233   53233   56478   76928

The NAs have been successfully removed!

income_average, total_number_of_routes_600 & num_vendex_nearby_300 do not show statistical significance. This is because their p-value is greater than 0.05

By default, R considers 95% confidence intervals and a p-value above 0.05 for a variable means that the probability of the coefficient of that variable being 0 is high. Hence we deduce that the coefficients for all the variables with p-value greater than 0.05 to be 0.

Calculating the real daily sales of top20% and bottom20% machines

#Calculating the 80th & 20th percentile
percentile_80 = quantile(df$.preds, 0.8)
percentile_20 = quantile(df$.preds, 0.2)

#Storing the machines with top 20% sales in top_20_percent dataframe
top_20_percent <- df %>%
                  select(machine, .preds) %>%
                  filter(.preds >= percentile_80)

#Storing the machines with bottom 20% sales in bottom_20_percent dataframe
bottom_20_percent <- df %>%
                    select(machine, .preds) %>%
                    filter(.preds <= percentile_20)

top_20_pcnt_sales = round(sum(top_20_percent$.preds))
bottom_20_pcnt_sales = round(sum(bottom_20_percent$.preds))
req_ratio = round(top_20_pcnt_sales/bottom_20_pcnt_sales,2)

Since the avg_daily_sales of location ii are higher than that of location i, we should setup the big machine in location ii.
